                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>New York</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <date>April 23, 54</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Rabbi Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I forward the<lb/>
                                        <sic>inclosed</sic> which I have<lb/> just
                                                  <sic>recieved</sic> in a letter<lb/> from my
                                        brother.<lb/> The prospects in
                                                  <placeName>Pal-<lb/>estine</placeName>—politically
                                        &amp; socially<lb/> are entirely favourable<lb/> to
                                        agricultural <sic>persuits</sic>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Oh can you not<lb/> influence those who<lb/> have
                                        the control of the<lb/> funds which are in<lb/>tended for
                                                  <placeName>Palestine</placeName> to<lb/> direct
                                        that a portion<lb/> of them be expended<lb/> in employing
                                        the</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>poor in learning agriculture,<lb/> as you propose in the
                                                  <date>Feb.</date><lb/> no of the “Occident.”</p>
                              <p>There can be no objection.<lb/> Your English brethren<lb/>
                                        approve—certainly our<lb/> practical &amp; economical<lb/>
                                        Americans will also.<lb/> They must disearn<add>?</add>
                                        the<lb/> great advantage of<lb/> aiding their brethren<lb/>
                                        to earn their own sub-<lb/>sistence in preference<lb/> to
                                        supporting them for<lb/>ever in idleness.</p>
                              <p>This place of appropri<lb/>ating your charities in<lb/> the
                                                  <placeName>Holy Land</placeName>, will
                                        cer<lb/>tainly become popular<lb/> in the minds of all<lb/>
                                        your reflecting brethren.</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>but as with any other<lb/> reform measure or new arrang<lb/>ment it
                                        will doubtless be<lb/> necessary to constantly<lb/>
                                        recommend and insist upon<lb/> its adoption.</p>
                              <p>Dear Sir—allow me to<lb/> express the hope that in<lb/> view of the
                                        certainty of an<lb/> ultimate success, &amp; of the<lb/>
                                        superior good to be attained,<lb/> you will persevere
                                        with<lb/> all possible energy &amp; dili<lb/>gence until the
                                        effort you<lb/> have so properly commenced<lb/> is fully
                                                  <sic>consumated</sic>.<lb/> Until those of your
                                        brethren<lb/> who leave the power,<lb/> decide fully to have
                                        their<lb/> funds expanded in learning<lb/> the destitute in
                                                  <placeName>Palestine</placeName></p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>how to maintain <hi rend="underline">themselves</hi><lb/> and thus
                                        become permanently<lb/> relieved from their poverty—<lb/>
                                        Our colony would not desire<lb/> to assume any
                                        responsibility<lb/> in relation to the direction<lb/> or
                                        control in the least<lb/> degree of your funds, which<lb/>
                                        should be continued at the dis<lb/>posal of the
                                                  R<add>?</add>.</p>
                              <p>Our Farmers &amp; Mechanics<lb/> will afford the requisite
                                        in<lb/>struction &amp; gratis, until<lb/> the men are
                                        sufficiently<lb/> advanced to support them<lb/>selves. Your
                                        Rabbis will<lb/> however disburse to them<lb/> their usual
                                        allowance in the<lb/> form of wages, to enable them<lb/> as
                                        at present to support<lb/> their families while they</p>
